# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1812-state-of-the-union-address
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] The **12th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from March 4, 1811, to March 4, 1813, during the third and fourth years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] During this congress, two new Senate seats were added for the new state of Louisiana.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] During this congress, one new House seat was added for the new state of Louisiana.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/12th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The first election for Virginia's 5th congressional district took place on February 2, 1789, for a two-year term to commence on March 4 of that year.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In a race that turned on the candidates' positions on the need for amendments (the Bill of Rights) to the recently ratified U.S.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Constitution, James Madison defeated James Monroe for a place in the House of Representatives of the First Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It is the only congressional election in U.S. history in which two future presidents opposed each other.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They put forward Monroe, a young but experienced politician who was a war hero wounded at the 1776 Battle of Trenton, as a candidate for the seat.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe did not seek the contest, but once drafted campaigned vigorously.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite bitterly cold weather, the two candidates debated outdoors; traveling after one such meeting, Madison suffered frostbite on his face.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although Madison had earlier stated that amendments to the Constitution were not necessary, during the campaign he took the position that they were, but should be proposed by Congress, rather than by an Article V Convention that Anti-Federalists such as Monroe and Henry supported.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison won the election comfortably, to the satisfaction of his supporters such as President-elect George Washington.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The race did not affect Madison's friendship with Monroe, who was elected to the Senate in 1790, and who would serve as Madison's Secretary of State and succeed him as president in 1817.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Madison was born on March 16, 1751 (March 5, 1750, Old Style), at the Belle Grove plantation near Port Conway, Virginia.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He grew up on his parents' estate of Montpelier, and was involved in politics from a young age, serving on the local Committee of Safety at age 23.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He represented Orange County in the Fifth Virginia Convention of 1776.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After service on the Virginia Council of State, where he forged a lifelong friendship with Governor Thomas Jefferson, he was elected to the Second Continental Congress becoming its youngest member.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was one of Virginia's delegates to the Constitutional Convention in 1787, and helped persuade General George Washington to be its chair, which gave the convention the moral authority to propose a new plan of government.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was the originator of the Virginia Plan that became the basis of the federal government proposed by the convention.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Monroe was born April 28, 1758, in Westmoreland County, Virginia, the son of prosperous planters, Spence Monroe and Elizabeth Jones Monroe.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] By 1774, the year he entered the College of William & Mary, both his parents had died.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In early 1776, he joined the Virginia militia and became an officer in the Continental Army, later that year being severely wounded at the Battle of Trenton.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He left Continental service in 1779, and was made a colonel in the state militia.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the war, Monroe studied law under Jefferson and was elected to the House of Delegates in 1782, and to the Congress of the Confederation in New York in 1783, where he sought to expand the powers of that body.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1784, Madison was told by Jefferson that Monroe wanted to begin a correspondence with him, beginning a relationship that would last until Monroe's death in 1831.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men differed over whether their state should ratify the Constitution at the Virginia Ratifying Convention, with Madison in favor and Monroe against.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Opponents deemed the proposed national government to be too powerful, and many wanted a second constitutional convention in order to place limits on it.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite their efforts, Virginia narrowly ratified the Constitution on June 25, 1788.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe, like Jefferson, believed that there needed to be a Bill of Rights protecting fundamental liberties from infringement by the new federal government.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Ratification had not been a major issue in the Virginia legislative elections of 1788, since it was expected to be decided by the Ratifying Convention that had just been chosen by the voters.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] When the General Assembly convened in October 1788, though, it had a majority of Anti-Federalist members, and was led by Henry, a member of the House of Delegates for Prince Edward County.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry sought to avenge the Anti-Federalist defeat at the Ratifying Convention, and also believed Madison would not seek amendments, or would do so in a lukewarm fashion.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On October 31, the General Assembly re-elected Madison to his seat in the lame-duck Confederation Congress, a body that would cease to exist with the coming of the new federal government.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's motives in allowing this are uncertain, with some historians stating it was to keep Madison in New York, far from the elections for Congress taking place in Virginia.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Historian Chris DeRose hypothesizes that Madison's seat there was his if he wanted it, and his acceptance meant that he expected to remain in New York (where the new Congress would convene) and win his seat in Virginia without needing to campaign.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison, who sought election to the House of Representatives, yielded to Washington and the Federalist minority in the legislature and allowed his name to be put forward in the legislature's election for Virginia's two U.S. senators—until 1913, senators were elected by the state legislatures.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry nominated two Anti-Federalists, Richard Henry Lee and William Grayson, while Madison was the sole Federalist named.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry told the General Assembly that Madison was "unworthy of the confidence of the people" and that his election "would terminate in producing rivulets of blood throughout the land".
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's nominees were elected, Lee with 98 votes and Grayson with 86, while the defeated Madison gained 77.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly turned its attention to dividing the state into congressional districts.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's home county, Orange, was placed in a district with seven others, five of which had elected representatives to the Ratifying Convention who had opposed ratification, while Orange and one other had voted in favor and one county's delegation had split its vote.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly required that candidates live in the district, a qualification not found in the federal Constitution.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Fauquier County, closely associated with Orange both geographically and economically, had supported ratification, but was excluded despite the efforts of Federalists.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite some stating that Henry had contrived a district in which Madison was sure to be defeated, Thomas Rogers Hunter in a journal article examined the question, and concluded, "the district was compact and bounded on all sides by natural geographic features.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Simply put, Patrick Henry did not attempt to gerrymander James Madison out of a seat in the first U.S.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Congress." Virginia's 5th congressional district consisted of the counties of Albemarle, Amherst, Culpeper, Fluvanna, Goochland, Louisa, Orange and Spotsylvania.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Some of these counties were later divided, so the district that Madison contested also included the present-day counties of Greene, Madison, Nelson and Rappahannock.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] French Strother, a long-time Virginia legislator from Culpeper County who had opposed ratification at the Virginia Convention, was solicited as a candidate to oppose Madison, but declined.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] William Cabell, of Amherst County, was also considered as an Anti-Federalist candidate but Monroe was selected instead.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Both Strother and Cabell threw their support behind Monroe.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A resident of Spotsylvania County, Monroe was reluctant to run against his friend Madison, but was probably encouraged by Henry, George Mason and other Anti-Federalists, though discouraged by his uncle, Joseph Jones.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] His service in the Revolutionary War, and his political service after it, were electoral assets.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The selection of Monroe was enough to worry Washington: "Sorry indeed should I be if Mr.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Federalist Henry Lee wrote to him, "I profess myself pleased with your exclusion from the senate & I wish it may so happen in the lower house [in which case] you will be left qualified to take part in the administration, which is the place proper for you".
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, Henry Lee believed Madison would win, calling Monroe "the beau".
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison disliked electioneering, but realized he would have to campaign hard to win the race.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Fifth District race would be the only congressional election in history to oppose two future U.S. presidents.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The largest issue in the campaign was the question of a Bill of Rights protecting personal freedoms as amendments to the Constitution.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's view had been that these were unnecessary as the Federal government had only limited power and that in any event, the new government should be allowed to operate for a time before changes were made to the Constitution.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To take such a stance in the campaign would be political suicide, and Madison recognized that there was widespread support for such amendments.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] But he felt it to be important that Congress proposed them, believing that route to be a quicker, easier, and safer means of passage than an Article V convention, which was favored by the Anti-Federalists such as Monroe.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, he was skeptical about the effect of such amendments, calling them "parchment barriers", ineffective if the Federal government was determined to bypass them.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He told the voters that if elected, he would work diligently for the passage of a Bill of Rights.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's earlier stances made it easy to depict him in this light.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge to support a Bill of Rights if elected left the question of direct taxation as the major difference between them.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe believed the power of the Federal government to directly tax the citizens to be not only unnecessary, but injurious to American liberty.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He felt the government could raise money by tariffs, by the sale of public lands, or by borrowing.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison responded that were the Federal government unable to tax citizens directly, tariffs would be the major source of revenue, and this would disproportionately hurt the South, which had few manufactures and imported heavily from overseas.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He also stated that having federal taxes paid in each state would help bind the nation together as giving each a financial stake in the Union's success.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been in New York, helping to wrap up the affairs of the old Congress of the Confederation.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He received letters from other parts of Virginia from those who believed the residency requirement unconstitutional, offering to have him run there, but he preferred to run in his home district, and he declined.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A trip to Virginia on horseback or in a carriage would be personally hard on Madison, then suffering from a bad case of hemorrhoids.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On December 8, 1788, he wrote to Jefferson (who was in Paris) that he would return to Virginia to campaign for his election, a decision prompted in part by warnings from Virginians that he could not win without personally fighting for the seat.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He arrived at Washington's plantation, Mount Vernon, on December 18, for a visit that lasted until he returned home to Orange County and his estate, Montpelier, just after Christmas.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] From the time Madison arrived in Virginia, the weather was unusually cold and snowy; the candidates often had to speak in freezing conditions, and the last weekend before the election saw 10 inches (250 mm) of snow.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Aware he was not an orator of Henry's quality, Madison launched a letter-writing campaign, advocating for the new Constitution; though initially taken by surprise, Monroe also set out his positions in letters.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It was Madison's intent, in writing to key citizens in each community, both to enlist support, and have the recipients circulate the letters locally or publish them in local newspapers.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] For Monroe's part, according to DeRose, he "poured himself into the campaign with frenetic energy, determined to campaign everywhere, to personally engage voters, and to make liberal use of his pen to correspond with community leaders.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Considering him as being able to render his Country Great Services on this important occasion".
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On January 7, 1789, Virginians chose electors who would vote for the first U.S. president.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The districts for this were not coextensive with congressional districts, since Virginia was entitled to 12 electors but only 10 congressmen.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Still, six of the counties in the Fifth District were in the same district for choosing an elector, and the race featured a Federalist and Anti-Federalist, though both were pledged to vote for Washington for president.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Goochland and Louisa counties were not in that electoral district, but Buckingham County was.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Federalist, Edward Stevens, was elected, and outpolled his opponent within the Fifth District, but both parties took hope from the result, with the Anti-Federalists cheered by the fact that Stevens had easily taken Spotsylvania County, where the local favorite Monroe would presumably do better.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates sought to appeal to the local religious communities, of which the Baptists were the most influential.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] That community had taken the position that the Constitution did not provide sufficient protection for their religious liberty.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge of support for amendments defused much of the Anti-Federalist anger against him.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men were quite friendly with each other, and decided to travel together between debates, riding from courthouse to courthouse, making speeches before large crowds.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] These debates showed the physical contrast between the tall, athletic Monroe, who had a full head of brown hair, and the short, slender Madison and his receding hairline.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They often rode together, ate together, and lodged in the same room.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 18th century Virginia, Court Day, a different day in each local county, was not only an opportunity for lawyers and judges to try cases, but a social gathering, including fairs, markets, and other events.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates addressed those present, sometimes speaking for hours to the largest crowds they were likely to find during the campaign.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry Lee wrote to Washington three days later, "Mr Madison is gaining ground fast but still he is involved in much doubt & difficulty.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The debate that DeRose deemed perhaps the most significant of the race took place one evening at the Hebron Lutheran Church in Culpeper (today in Madison County).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Lutherans, like the Baptists, had been persecuted in America, and generally voted as a bloc to maximize their influence.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe and Madison attended the worship service, after which there was musical entertainment featuring fiddles.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They and the congregation then went outside, and the two candidates debated on the front porch as the congregation stood in the bitter cold, with snow on the ground, likely for hours.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Riding away afterwards, likely home to Montpelier, Madison suffered a frostbitten nose.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In his old age, former president Madison would tell the story of that night, and point to the left side of his nose, saying he had battle scars.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] White males who were 21 years of age or older and who owned 50 acres (20 ha) of unimproved land or half that with a house were eligible to vote in the Fifth District.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Approximately 5,189 voters formed the district's electorate.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Per the 1790 census, there were 11,231 free white males age over 16 in the district, so about half of free white men were able to vote.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The total population (including women, slaves and children) of the district was 91,007, so the electorate made up less than 6% of the total population, and perhaps 12–15% of those aged over 21.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] There was no secret ballot in Virginia elections in 1789; voters entered the local courthouse and publicly declared their votes, to be recorded by a clerk.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The elections were administered by county sheriffs, normally the senior justice of the peace who had not already served in that capacity.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Due to the bitterly cold weather in the Fifth District, the sheriffs in some counties extended voting beyond February 2, allowing more voters to reach their county courthouse.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] This was not authorized by Virginia law, but had also occurred in the voting for presidential electors the previous month.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To get out the vote, Madison's supporters sent wagons around to transport voters to the polls.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They brought one very old man from a distance, and he listened to them talk and asked if the Monroe spoken of was the son of Spence Monroe, formerly of Westmoreland County.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On being told he was, the man declared he would vote for James Monroe, for "I do not know James Madison", but Spence Monroe had once fed him, clothed him and sheltered him.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Once the polls closed, the local sheriff went to the door of the courthouse and proclaimed the result.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It took time for complete results to be compiled; partial returns were printed in newspapers.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On February 10, the sheriffs of the eight counties of the Fifth District met at Albemarle's courthouse, as the county first named in the election statute, to certify the results.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Their returns indicated that Madison won the election with 1,308 votes to 972 for Monroe.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In Madison's home county of Orange, he received 216 votes to Monroe's 9, in Culpeper 256 to Monroe's 103; he won Albemarle County by 69 votes and Louisa by 104.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had given considerable attention to Orange, apparently spending the day of the polls there despite the urgings of some supporters to base himself for the day in a more populous county, and two-thirds of his margin of victory came from Orange.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Strong Baptist support for Madison there contributed to the outcome.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been able to hold down the margin in strongly Anti-Federalist Amherst to 246–145 for Monroe, who also took his home county of Spotsylvania by 74 votes, Fluvanna by 21 and Goochland by 1 vote.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Baptists favored Madison due to his record of support for religious liberty.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the election, Madison wrote to Jefferson, "It was my misfortune to be thrown into a contest with our friend, Col.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The occasion produced considerable efforts among our respective friends.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] According to Stewart, "Barely thirty years old, Monroe had time to make his way.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In the House of Representatives, Madison introduced and guided to passage the amendments that became known as the Bill of Rights.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He broke with Washington over the administration's policies, and allied with Jefferson, helping gain the latter's election to the presidency, and became his Secretary of State in 1801.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He succeeded Jefferson as president in 1809.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although defeated for Congress, Monroe's frequent court appearances as a lawyer kept him in the public eye in Virginia.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1790, after Grayson's death, the General Assembly elected him to the U.S.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He served thereafter in a number of offices, including, twice, Governor of Virginia, and in 1811 Madison named Monroe as Secretary of State.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe was elected president in succession to Madison in 1816, taking office the following year.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1790-and-1791-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The state of union is an address, in the United States, given by the president to a joint session of Congress, the United States House of Representatives and United States Senate.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The United States constitution requires the president "from time to time give to the Congress Information of the State of the Union." Today the state of the union address is given as a speech, though this is not a requirement of the constitution.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] George Washington chose to address the Congress in a speech annually; on October 25, 1791, he gave his third speech.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] A major concern at the time was the raising of taxes, as Congress were arguing whether they had the constitutional power to do so.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Revenues for the Federal Government were at that time mostly collected on import duties.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Alexander Hamilton, the then Secretary of the Treasury, felt these had been raised to as high a level as was reasonable, and a new income stream was necessary.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Before the speech, Congress had been debating where to put the capital.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Finally, through a deal made between Alexander Hamilton, James Madison, and Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson, they came to a conclusion.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] This deal is known as the Compromise of 1790.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the U.S. was in possession of the original thirteen colonies, along with the land gained in the Treaty of Paris.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The Treaty of Paris ended the revolutionary war; in it, America was granted territory as far west as the Mississippi River.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Known as the year of "Great Immigration" 1788 was the year many Americans moved west.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On October 18, 1790, the Ohio tribe defeated an expedition of American troops near Fort Wayne, Indiana; this signified the beginning of the hostilities in the North West territory.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On March 30, 1791, construction of the Knoxville Road began, linking to the Wilderness Road and to Knoxville.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The road opened up more frontier area for settlements.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] In September 1791, there was much hostility in Ohio territory; this caused Americans to build forts at Hamilton, St.Clair, Jefferson, Greenville and Recovery.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the Census Act had been in place for just over a year and a half.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The act called for a routine census of the United States, and was passed by Congress on March 1, 1790.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He acknowledged that there had been some "degree of discontent" about the Whiskey Tax, and that it was not perfect, but he was going to keep it anyway.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He said "revision of the provision will be found advisable." The Whiskey tax was one Hamilton wanted enacted as part of a funding system for the new country.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the debt has been mostly dealt with, but there might be a few things that still need to be paid off and he urges the House of Representatives to pay off any lingering debts, and there will be exact numbers coming to them soon.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] "The part of the debt of the United States which remains unsubscribed will naturally engage your further deliberation," Washington is saying the House of Representatives must talk further on the debt that has not yet been dealt with.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington briefly mentions the "completion of the census of the inhabitants," he is talking about the Census of 1790.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that "the present population of the United States borders on 4,000,000 persons".
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The number was 3,929,625 according to the 1790 Census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the end of the speech he comments on "the militia, the post office and post roads, the mint, weights and measures, a provision for the sale of the vacant lands of the United States." Washington wants to send militia to particularly vulnerable places in the US, as they are a new country.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the United States must have "systematic and solid arrangements, exposed as little as possible to the hazards of fortuitous circumstances." He beliefs that there must be more post offices and roads, to create unity with in the country.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] As well to make sure that there is no :misrepresentation and misconception" of the "laws and proceedings of the Government." He then remarks that there is a scarcity of smaller American change and that there must be more put into place.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington then goes on to say that the wright and measures of the country must be uniform and conducive to public convenience.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington spent a good deal of the speech trying to convince the Native Americans to become part of the United States, as well as convincing the citizens of the country of the importance of doing so.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He pushed the Senate to ratify the treaties pending before that House with the Cherokees and Six Nations of Indians (Iroquois Confederation).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He stated that the House needed to act on bills to ensure the financial security of the nation.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-and-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The **1792 State of the Union Address** was delivered by George Washington to Congress on Tuesday, November 6, 1792.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] It was presented in Philadelphia's Congress Hall.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The president commented on continued incursions by Native Americans into frontier settlements.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Notably, the address contains mention of the Chickamaugas, a part of the Cherokee tribe that committed multiple incursions in frontiers along the Tennessee River.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The President noted that the incursions were a violation of the Treaty of Holston.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Still further to promote and secure these inestimable ends there is nothing which can have a more powerful tendency than the careful cultivation of harmony, combined with a due regard to stability, in the public councils.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] The **1793 State of the Union Address** was given by George Washington, the first president of the United States.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] It was given in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania at Congress Hall.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] During the address, Washington spoke of Peace through strength.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] He also urged the expansion of the legal code and jurisdiction of the courts in order to enforce the laws of the land.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1793-state-of-the-union-address] The President reported on progress for peace with the Creek and Cherokee tribes and noted that trade with the tribes should be expanded where possible.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] The **1812 State of the Union Address** was delivered by the fourth president of the United States, James Madison, on November 4, 1812.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] Addressing the 12th United States Congress, Madison reflected on the early stages of the War of 1812 and provided updates on the military, diplomatic, and economic situation facing the nation.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] Madison began by expressing gratitude for the prosperity and health experienced by the country, but acknowledged the challenges of being at war with Great Britain.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] He outlined the early setbacks of the war, particularly the surrender of Detroit by General William Hull, which had been a major blow to U.S. efforts to secure the Michigan Territory and Canada.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] Despite this defeat, Madison praised the national spirit, noting that it had galvanized citizens from Kentucky, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Virginia to defend the frontier.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] Madison condemned the British for employing Native American allies, accusing them of inciting violence against American settlers.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] He contrasted the British actions with the U.S. government's policy of promoting peace and civilization among Native Americans, and he decried the brutal tactics used by British-aligned forces.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] The president also addressed the American victory in the naval battle between the USS *Constitution*, commanded by Captain Isaac Hull, and the British frigate HMS *Guerriere*.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] This victory was hailed as proof of American naval prowess and provided a morale boost for the country.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] Madison reported that diplomatic efforts to resolve the conflict had failed.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] Despite attempts to negotiate an armistice, Britain refused to suspend its practice of impressment of American sailors, a key issue that had led to the war.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] As a result, Madison urged Congress to continue the war effort and to bolster the military with additional resources.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] On the economic front, Madison noted that the war had disrupted trade but reassured Congress that revenue collections were sufficient to cover government expenses and repay portions of the public debt.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] He also called for increased support for the nation's manufacturing sector to reduce reliance on foreign goods.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] Madison concluded by reaffirming the justness of the war, stating that it was fought not for conquest but to defend American rights and sovereignty.
[src:1812-state-of-the-union-address/1812-state-of-the-union-address] He expressed confidence in the nation's ability to persevere and achieve a peace that would secure its maritime independence.
